'''Mikumano Shrine''' (三熊野神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Kakegawa|ja|掛川市|12=draft}}, {{ill|Shizuoka Prefecture|ja|静岡県|12=draft}}, Japan. Known for its crest, the "Right Three Chōji Tomoe," it is associated with the {{ill|Kumano Sanzan|ja|熊野三山|12=draft}} shrines.

== Overview ==
[[File:2rin-yatai-yokosuka.jpg|thumb|200px|Two-wheeled floats at the {{ill|Enshū Yokosuka Mikumano Shrine Grand Festival|ja|遠州横須賀三熊野神社大祭|12=draft}}]]
The shrine is located near {{ill|Yokosuka Castle|ja|横須賀城|12=draft}}. According to tradition, it was established during the early 8th century (Taibō era) under the orders of {{ill|Emperor Monmu|ja|文武天皇|12=draft}}. The deities enshrined are {{ill|Izanami|ja|伊邪那美命|12=draft}}, {{ill|Hayatama no Mikoto|ja|速玉男命|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Kotoshironushi|ja|事解男命|12=draft}}, who are believed to have been transferred from the Kumano Sanzan shrines. Together with {{ill|Takamatsu Shrine (Omaezaki)|ja|高松神社|12=draft}} in {{ill|Omaezaki|ja|御前崎市|12=draft}} and {{ill|Ogasajinja Shrine|ja|小笠神社|12=draft}} in Kakegawa, Mikumano Shrine is referred to as one of the "Kumano Sanzan of Enshū."

== Festivals ==
=== Enshū Yokosuka Mikumano Shrine Grand Festival ===
The annual festival, held over three days starting on the first Friday of April, is a major event. Known as the {{ill|Enshū Yokosuka Mikumano Shrine Grand Festival|ja|遠州横須賀三熊野神社大祭|12=draft}}, it features processions with {{ill|mikoshi|ja|神輿|12=draft}} and the pulling of two-wheeled floats called "Neri" (祢里), drawing large crowds of visitors.<ref name="kakegawashiyakusho20080609">Kakegawa City Hall, Commerce, Labor and Tourism Division. "[http://lgportal.city.kakegawa.shizuoka.jp/kanko/k_jyoho/mikumanojinja_taisai/mikuma.jsp Mikumano Shrine Grand Festival]." Retrieved June 9, 2008.</ref>

=== Mikodaki Ceremony (Child-Blessing Ritual) ===
On the second day of the festival, the Mikodaki Ceremony, or child-blessing ritual, takes place. Participants carry a doll called "Onenneko-sama" as part of the procession. This ritual attracts many visitors seeking blessings for children.<ref>{{Cite web
| author = Sansha Gongen Mikumano Shrine
| url = http://www4.tokai.or.jp/mikuma/mikodaki.html
| title = Mikodaki Ceremony
| accessdate = July 31, 2016 }}</ref>

== History ==
Mikumano Shrine was established during the early 8th century by {{ill|Emperor Monmu|ja|文武天皇|12=draft}}. According to tradition, the shrine was built after Empress {{ill|Fujiwara no Miyako|ja|藤原宮子|12=draft}} prayed to the Kumano Sanzan shrines for a safe childbirth. Her prayer was answered with the birth of {{ill|Emperor Shōmu|ja|聖武天皇|12=draft}}, prompting the establishment of three shrines in gratitude.<ref name="kakegawashiyakusho">Kakegawa City Hall. "[http://lgportal.city.kakegawa.shizuoka.jp/kanko/k_jyoho/mikumanojinja_taisai/mikuma_2.jsp Introduction to the Mikumano Shrine Grand Festival]."</ref>

Over time, the shrine became a center for {{ill|Kumano faith|ja|熊野信仰|12=draft}}. In 1335, {{ill|Nitta Yoshisada|ja|新田義貞|12=draft}} prayed for victory and reportedly dedicated a bell gifted by {{ill|Kusunoki Masashige|ja|楠木正成|12=draft}}. After {{ill|Tokugawa Ieyasu|ja|徳川家康|12=draft}} built Yokosuka Castle in 1578, the shrine gained further prominence among the local rulers and residents.<ref>{{Cite web
| author = Sansha Gongen Mikumano Shrine
| url = http://www4.tokai.or.jp/mikuma/about.html
| title = About Mikumano Shrine
| accessdate = July 31, 2016 }}</ref>

