[[File:2rin-yatai-yokosuka.jpg|thumb|200px|Two-wheeled floats at the {{ill|Enshū Yokosuka Mikumano Shrine Grand Festival|ja|遠州横須賀三熊野神社大祭|qq=draft}}]]
The shrine is located near {{ill|Yokosuka Castle|ja|横須賀城|qq=draft}}. According to tradition, it was established during the early 8th century (Taibō era) under the orders of {{ill|Emperor Monmu|ja|文武天皇|qq=draft}}. The deities enshrined are {{ill|Izanami|ja|伊邪那美命|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Hayatama no Mikoto|ja|速玉男命|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Kotoshironushi|ja|事解男命|qq=draft}}, who are believed to have been transferred from the Kumano Sanzan shrines. Together with {{ill|Takamatsu Shrine (Omaezaki)|ja|高松神社|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Omaezaki|ja|御前崎市|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Ogasajinja Shrine|ja|小笠神社|qq=draft}} in Kakegawa, Mikumano Shrine is referred to as one of the "Kumano Sanzan of Enshū."

== Festivals ==
=== Enshū Yokosuka Mikumano Shrine Grand Festival ===
The annual festival, held over three days starting on the first Friday of April, is a major event. Known as the {{ill|Enshū Yokosuka Mikumano Shrine Grand Festival|ja|遠州横須賀三熊野神社大祭|qq=draft}}, it features processions with {{ill|mikoshi|ja|神輿|qq=draft}} and the pulling of two-wheeled floats called "Neri" (祢里), drawing large crowds of visitors.<ref name="kakegawashiyakusho20080609">Kakegawa City Hall, Commerce, Labor and Tourism Division. "[http://lgportal.city.kakegawa.shizuoka.jp/kanko/k_jyoho/mikumanojinja_taisai/mikuma.jsp Mikumano Shrine Grand Festival]." Retrieved June 9, 2008.</ref>

=== Mikodaki Ceremony (Child-Blessing Ritual) ===
On the second day of the festival, the Mikodaki Ceremony, or child-blessing ritual, takes place. Participants carry a doll called "Onenneko-sama" as part of the procession. This ritual attracts many visitors seeking blessings for children.<ref>{{Cite web
| author = Sansha Gongen Mikumano Shrine
| url = http://www4.tokai.or.jp/mikuma/mikodaki.html
| title = Mikodaki Ceremony
| accessdate = July 31, 2016 }}</ref>

== History ==
Mikumano Shrine was established during the early 8th century by {{ill|Emperor Monmu|ja|文武天皇|qq=draft}}. According to tradition, the shrine was built after Empress {{ill|Fujiwara no Miyako|ja|藤原宮子|qq=draft}} prayed to the Kumano Sanzan shrines for a safe childbirth. Her prayer was answered with the birth of {{ill|Emperor Shōmu|ja|聖武天皇|qq=draft}}, prompting the establishment of three shrines in gratitude.<ref name="kakegawashiyakusho">Kakegawa City Hall. "[http://lgportal.city.kakegawa.shizuoka.jp/kanko/k_jyoho/mikumanojinja_taisai/mikuma_2.jsp Introduction to the Mikumano Shrine Grand Festival]."</ref>

Over time, the shrine became a center for {{ill|Kumano faith|ja|熊野信仰|1=Kumano Three Shrines|lt=Kumano faith|qq=draft}}. In 1335, {{ill|Nitta Yoshisada|ja|新田義貞|qq=draft}} prayed for victory and reportedly dedicated a bell gifted by {{ill|Kusunoki Masashige|ja|楠木正成|qq=draft}}. After {{ill|Tokugawa Ieyasu|ja|徳川家康|qq=draft}} built Yokosuka Castle in 1578, the shrine gained further prominence among the local rulers and residents.<ref>{{Cite web
| author = Sansha Gongen Mikumano Shrine
| url = http://www4.tokai.or.jp/mikuma/about.html
| title = About Mikumano Shrine
| accessdate = July 31, 2016 }}</ref>

== Cultural Properties ==
The following are designated cultural properties of Shizuoka Prefecture and Kakegawa City:<ref name="kakegawashikyoikuiinkai20070401">Kakegawa City Education Board, Cultural Property Division. "[http://www.city.kakegawa.shizuoka.jp/kanko/bunkazai/siteiitirannhyio.html List of Designated Cultural Properties]." Retrieved September 23, 2011.</ref>

=== Shizuoka Prefecture Designations ===
* '''Main Hall''' (Tangible Cultural Property, Architecture)
* '''44 Ema Paintings''' (Tangible Cultural Property, Paintings)

=== Kakegawa City Designations ===
* '''Tengu Mask''' (Tangible Cultural Property, Sculpture)
* '''Komainu''' (Tangible Cultural Property, Sculpture)

== Subsidiary Shrines ==
The shrine grounds also host three subsidiary shrines:
* '''Suwa Shrine''' - Deities: {{ill|Takeminakata|ja|建御名方神|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Ōkuninushi|ja|大国主神|qq=draft}}
* '''Tenjin Shrine''' - deity: {{ill|Tenjin (kami)|ja|天満天神|qq=draft}}
* '''Okuno Shrine''' - deity: Okuno Saemon Koreyoshi Kyo

