| accessdate = July 31, 2016 }}</ref>

== History ==
Mikumano Shrine was established during the early 8th century by {{ill|Emperor Monmu|en|Emperor Monmu|qid=Q357246|lt=Emperor Monmu|1=Emperor Monmu}}. According to tradition, the shrine was built after Empress {{ill|Fujiwara no Miyako|ja|藤原宮子|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fujiwara no Miyako|1=Fujiwara no Miyako|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q11623185}} prayed to the Kumano Sanzan shrines for a safe childbirth. Her prayer was answered with the birth of {{ill|Emperor Shōmu|en|Emperor Shōmu|qid=Q349263|lt=Emperor Shōmu|1=Emperor Shōmu}}, prompting the establishment of three shrines in gratitude.<ref name="kakegawashiyakusho">Kakegawa City Hall. "[http://lgportal.city.kakegawa.shizuoka.jp/kanko/k_jyoho/mikumanojinja_taisai/mikuma_2.jsp Introduction to the Mikumano Shrine Grand Festival]."</ref>

Over time, the shrine became a center for {{ill|Kumano faith|ja|熊野信仰|1=Kumano Faith|2=ja|3=熊野信仰|qid=Q135501741}}{{efn|The religion of [[Kumano Shrines]]|1=Kumano shrine|lt=Kumano Three Shrines|lt=Kumano faith|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano faith|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Three Shrines|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 熊野三山}}. In 1335, {{ill|Nitta Yoshisada|en|Nitta Yoshisada|qid=Q1328796|lt=Nitta Yoshisada|1=Nitta Yoshisada}} prayed for victory and reportedly dedicated a bell gifted by {{ill|Kusunoki Masashige|en|Kusunoki Masashige|qid=Q382234|lt=Kusunoki Masashige|1=Kusunoki Masashige}}. After {{ill|Tokugawa Ieyasu|en|Tokugawa Ieyasu|qid=Q171977|lt=Tokugawa Ieyasu|1=Tokugawa Ieyasu}} built Yokosuka Castle in 1578, the shrine gained further prominence among the local rulers and residents.<ref>{{Cite web
| author = Sansha Gongen Mikumano Shrine
| url = http://www4.tokai.or.jp/mikuma/about.html
| title = About Mikumano Shrine
| accessdate = July 31, 2016 }}</ref>

== Cultural Properties ==
The following are designated cultural properties of Shizuoka Prefecture and Kakegawa City:<ref name="kakegawashikyoikuiinkai20070401">Kakegawa City Education Board, Cultural Property Division. "[http://www.city.kakegawa.shizuoka.jp/kanko/bunkazai/siteiitirannhyio.html List of Designated Cultural Properties]." Retrieved September 23, 2011.</ref>

=== Shizuoka Prefecture Designations ===
* '''Main Hall''' (Tangible Cultural Property, Architecture)
* '''44 Ema Paintings''' (Tangible Cultural Property, Paintings)

=== Kakegawa City Designations ===
* '''Tengu Mask''' (Tangible Cultural Property, Sculpture)
* '''Komainu''' (Tangible Cultural Property, Sculpture)

== Subsidiary Shrines ==
The shrine grounds also host three subsidiary shrines:
* '''Suwa Shrine''' - Deities: {{ill|Takeminakata|en|Takeminakata|qid=Q9150391|qid=Q9150391|lt=Takeminakata|1=Takeminakata}}, {{ill|Ōkuninushi|ja|大国主神|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōkuninushi|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 大国主}}
* '''Tenjin Shrine''' - deity: {{ill|Tenjin (kami)|ja|天満天神|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenjin (kami)|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 天満大自在天神|1=Tenjin (kami)|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q1753428}}
* '''Okuno Shrine''' - deity: Okuno Saemon Koreyoshi Kyo

